* DONE cite Bekaert et al paper, intuition Stambaugh bias
  :PROPERTIES:
  :ARCHIVE_TIME: 2015-09-27 Sun 16:38
  :ARCHIVE_FILE: ~/pred/pred.org
  :ARCHIVE_OLPATH: Next actions
  :ARCHIVE_CATEGORY: pred
  :ARCHIVE_TODO: DONE
  :END:
Yes we definitely need to cite that paper. Sorry I forgot about
that. An important point is the following (which Caroline Pflueger
reminded me of): In dividend-yield predictions of stock returns,
Stambaugh bias inflates the R^2 and coefficients, and so makes the
predictability spuriously stronger. But in regressions of bond returns
on the yield curve, it works the other way, as shown by Bekaert et
al--the small-sample issues make the predictability weaker, i.e.,
accounting for it makes the rejections of the EH stronger. I
personally don't have great intuition for this (yet) but that's the
common view. I think this is what Cochrane had in mind when he was
talking about the sign of delta and that it matters -- it does matter
for the evidence on PC1-PC3. This probably implies that in our
predictive regressions for bond returns the true p-values on PC1-PC3
are smaller than the ones we report, which would support our
conclusions that level and slope are robust predictors. Here are some
places where we could cite this paper: (a) in the introduction, (b) in
2.3, (c) in 3.1 when we discuss the sign of delta and/or when we
discuss the significance of PC1-PC3.

