** DONE sub-sample stability / how Cochrane thinks of their results
  - stability of the CP factor across samples
  - we don't attack their whole paper, but only the 4th PC
  - acknowledge what they do
  - be precise about what they do and what we do
  => try to come up with some numbers to support our handwaving
  - we want to acknowledge that they did some tests for subsample stability
  - but the stability they document is the predictive power of the CP factor
  - we agree that level/slope/curve are stable in their predictive power
  - and CP factor is mostly (76%) driven by those, so that's not inconsistent
  - so our results and theirs are in fact consistent
*** what they did
We did extensive subsample analysis, p. 10 here
http://faculty.chicagobooth.edu/john.cochrane/research/papers/cochrane_piazzesi_appendix.pdf
at least we recognize the importance of subsample stability, and
it¹s-not-one-data-point stability, and documented it.

Figure 6 and 7 of our paper
http://faculty.chicagobooth.edu/john.cochrane/research/papers/cochrane_piazzesi_bond_risk_premia.pdf
Show exactly that you can see the feature in the data that the
regressions are using, and that it is important across most of the
important data points of high and low returns. At least reference the
figures if you want to say you can¹t see it, but like subsample
stability, a pattern visible in many recessions (not influential data
points), visibility to the eye, and the connection to business cycles
(correlation of CP with unemployment) was at least a very important
part of our battery of is-it-real tests.

P. 29. Out of sample stability. We¹ve looked a lot at this. The main
failure of our regression out of sample comes from the nutty behavior
of the right hand variable in the 2008 financial crisis. The coupon
bond effect in that December 2008 sends the FB forward curve nuts, and
it predicts big things that of course did not happen. After that, it¹s
not bad.

The most recent graphs along with color versions of most of these
reliability tests are here FYI starting on p. 567
http://faculty.chicagobooth.edu/john.cochrane/teaching/35150_advanced_investments/week_9_notes.pdf

Additional extras if you scroll down to bond risk premia here
http://faculty.chicagobooth.edu/john.cochrane/research/index.htm#assetpricing

